Name: Elfreth, Sarah
text:
I was asked by a reporter if there was anything I could agree with the President on during last night‚Äôs speech. There were moments‚Äîfew and far between‚Äîthat I could find a glimmer of common ground: supporting our servicemembers and first responders, leading the world in innovation and resurrecting shipbuilding in the United States, and ending childhood cancer. 
 
But we can‚Äôt end childhood cancer while slashing cancer research funding at the NIH and gutting Medicaid‚Äîthe number one health insurer of children in this nation. We can‚Äôt lead the world in innovation or build more ships while instituting unreasonable tariffs on aluminum and lumber from our trading partners, threatening universities, and turning our back on our democratic allies. We can‚Äôt support our servicemembers and first responders by demonizing individuals who want to serve in our military, slashing federal funding for public safety programs, and summarily firing civil servants. 
 
During the longest address by an Executive to the Congress in history, the President spent less than two minutes on the high cost of living that so many Americans are burdened by every day. He did not commit to protecting Social Security, Medicare, and Medicaid. In fact, he spent 13 minutes in ludicrous rants about fantastical (and wildly false) waste in Social Security and elsewhere in the federal government. 
 
I want to be clear that nothing about this Presidency‚Äìincluding his attacks on the civil service and the Constitution‚Äìis normal. I attended the Joint Address because I feel it is an important symbol of Congress as a co-equal branch of government, especially when the Executive is trying to test the limits of its powers. One-third of the American people voted for President Trump, one-third voted for someone else, and one-third did not feel passionately enough, heard, or represented to even vote. I‚Äôll be focused on listening and winning the hearts and minds of folks and colleagues in all three groups. That‚Äôs the path forward for us as a nation. That's the only way to earn the trust of colleagues across the aisle who can help us stop a lot of this calamity and nonsense. That's what the people of Maryland's 3rd Congressional District sent me here to do.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
I was grateful for the opportunity to participate in Tourette National Advocacy Day with @TouretteAssn and hear directly from individuals living with Tourette Syndrome and Tic Disorders, as well as the caregivers who stand by them. Among these dedicated advocates is Josie Stephens of Morrisville, whose efforts to improve the lives of those in our community and beyond are both inspiring and indispensable.

Since its founding in 1972, TAA has been at the forefront of raising awareness, advancing research, and providing critical resources for those affected by Tourette Syndrome. Their work has been pivotal in fostering understanding and driving meaningful progress.

As Co-Chair of the Bipartisan Disabilities Caucus, I am deeply committed to securing increased funding for neurodevelopmental research and am proud to continue working alongside passionate advocates like Josie and the Tourette Association of America. Together, we will ensure that securing the support and resources this community deserves remain a top priority here on Capitol Hill.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
Today marks 189 years since the fall of the Alamo. You‚Äôve heard the phrase a million times: ‚ÄúRemember the Alamo.‚Äù But why? What does that really mean?

The Alamo is more than a battlefield. More than a legend. It‚Äôs a dare. A dare to stand when you‚Äôre outnumbered. A dare to fight when surrender is easier. A dare to believe that principles‚Äîreal, hard, inconvenient principles‚Äîare worth more than comfort, safety, or even survival.

In 1836, 189 men took that dare. They weren‚Äôt all Texans, and they weren‚Äôt all soldiers. But they had one thing in common‚Äîthey refused to live under tyranny. They didn‚Äôt expect to win. They expected to die. And they did.

But here‚Äôs the thing: The Alamo wasn‚Äôt a defeat. It was a spark. A spark that burned into the soul of every Texan, igniting a fight that led to victory at San Jacinto. In just 18 minutes, Texas was free, and the world learned something about Americans‚Äîwe don‚Äôt run.

 The spirit of the Alamo is still alive today. It lives in every American who stands for what‚Äôs right, who refuses to back down, and who chooses principle over convenience.

So don‚Äôt just remember the Alamo. Live it.

The tourists aren't coming. Legacy businesses are leaving. The CNMI is on the cusp of economic collapse, and I am drafting a bill asking the federal government for a $400 million bailout as requested by my Governor.

Furthermore, we are being strangled by one-size-fits-all policies crafted by those who have no understanding of life on the ground in our community. For far too long, there have been conversations ABOUT the CNMI but not WITH the CNMI. These conversations often miss the point‚Äîour biggest threat is not the tourists. Although birth tourism is a problem, we are combating it like never before, and the CNMI has urged Congress to amend birthright citizenship in the Covenant. Our real threat right now happens to be economic collapse which would make us vulnerable to foreign adversaries and, in turn, put the nation at risk.

We have ONE industry in the Commonwealth and voices in DC are trying to take that away without supplying a viable alternative. I am urging @secrubio to work with embassies in Japan, Australia, the Philippines etc., to help us expand our tourism market. Additionally, we need fewer regulations on the CNMI, expanded labor access, and more economic relief.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 161, Roman Emperor Antoninus Pius died and is succeeded by co-Emperors Marcus Aurelius and Lucius Verus.

The partnership between the two emperors was largely peaceful and is seen as one of balance. Marcus focused on government and philosophy, while Lucius handled more ceremonial duties. Despite the challenges of their reign, including a devastating plague and military conflicts, the empire largely remained intact. Lucius died unexpectedly in 169, leaving Marcus to rule alone for the remainder of his life.

text:
Truth matters and here it is: This¬†NEVER¬†happened.

Our casework team traveled to Jefferson City to meet with both Republican and Democrat state-level counterparts to strengthen relationships and better serve our constituents. It is extremely unfortunate that an elected official feels the need to make up politically motivated lies about our team, who works tirelessly for the constituents of the Fourth District. They do not deserve this.

As a serious legislator, these types of reprehensible lies for relevancy are not only offensive to our team, but they are an embarrassing waste of time that does absolutely nothing to help the great people of Missouri.
The truth is that Rep. David Tyson Smith‚Äôs legislative assistant welcomed my team with open arms, smiles, and pleasant conversations. The meeting was full of professionalism and constructive conversations, and nobody ever discussed our public phone number (which is widely published on our website and on various Facebook posts).

After this great meeting, she even took the picture posted below. Does she look ‚Äúintimidated‚Äù to you? No‚Äîbecause this entire claim is a flat-out lie.

Our team would also never say they did not want to help constituents with the VA. On the contrary, they have done an incredible job helping to serve our constituents and they have worked diligently to deliver real results for casework claims. Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we shine a light on the extraordinary individuals who strengthen and uplift our community. But every so often, a story emerges that speaks to something even greater‚Äîthe quiet power of instinct, the courage found in the unexpected, and the steadfast presence of those who rise to meet the moment when it matters most.

As we approach International Women‚Äôs Day, we celebrate the women who keep our communities, our families, and our world moving forward‚Äînot with fanfare but with unwavering resolve. And this week, we recognize one such woman‚Äîa nurse whose quick thinking and steady hands turned what could have been a crisis into a moment of grace. Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero‚ÄîStephanie Frisco, a school nurse in the @Neshaminy_SD.
 
Last Thursday began like any other at Walter S. Miller Elementary School in Levittown‚Äîhallways filled with eager students, teachers shaping young minds, and the steady rhythm of a school day unfolding. But for Genevieve Peto, a devoted educator and expectant mother, the day would take a turn for which no lesson plan could have prepared her.
 
In moments like these, there is no time for hesitation‚Äîno second chances, no margin for error. With the steady confidence that defines true heroes, Stephanie assessed the situation, understood the urgency, and took command. There was no hospital. No team of doctors. Just the four walls of a school nurse‚Äôs office and a woman who refused to let uncertainty stand in her way. And in just ten minutes, despite never having delivered a child before, Stephanie helped Genevieve bring baby Cora safely into the world. A moment that could have ended in crisis became a story of courage, instinct, and grace under pressure.
 
Genevieve understands how easily that day could have taken a different turn. But when she looks back, it‚Äôs not with fear‚Äîit‚Äôs with profound gratitude. "She really was an angel, truly. We're beyond thankful."
 
What happened that day was more than a remarkable moment‚Äîit was a testament to the women who, day after day, step up, lean in, and do what needs to be done. We see it in the halls of our schools, where teachers like Genevieve shape the next generation with patience and wisdom.We see it in the hands of nurses like Stephanie, whose instincts and composure turn the unexpected into the extraordinary. We see it in mothers, daughters, sisters, and leaders‚Äîin the women who make the world work, often without fanfare, always with resilience.
 
Tomorrow, we celebrate International Women‚Äôs Day‚Äîbut every day, we honor the Stephanie Friscos and Genevieve Petos of the world‚Äîthe women whose strength, skill, and resolve keep our families, our communities, and our country moving forward. So today, let's applaud Stephanie for her quick thinking and steady hands, congratulate Genevieve, welcome baby Cora into a world made stronger by women like them, and celebrate the countless women in PA-1 and beyond who show us, time and again, what true resilience looks like.

Name: Clyburn, James E.
text:
On this 60th¬†anniversary of #BloodySunday, we remember the¬†men and women who were beaten, tear gassed, and risked their lives on the Edmund Pettus Bridge in Selma, Alabama to secure voting rights for all ‚Äî including my dear friend John Lewis.

The right to vote is a sacred cornerstone of our democracy. There must be free and unfettered access to the ballot box.

Name: Suozzi, Thomas R.
text:
On March 7, 1965, 60 years ago today, 25-year-old John Lewis stood alongside hundreds of brave individuals, crossing the Edmund Pettus Bridge to initiate the Selma to Montgomery march. Their act of peaceful protest was met with brutal violence; state troopers beat and tear-gassed the demonstrators, leaving Lewis with severe injuries, including a fractured skull. This harrowing event, now known as Bloody Sunday, became a catalyst for the historic Voting Rights Act of 1965.

For nearly three decades, John Lewis and fellow civil rights leaders honored the legacy of Bloody Sunday by crossing the Edmund Pettus Bridge arm-in-arm. In 2021, I had the profound privilege of joining my friend and colleague for his final commemoration of this significant chapter in our nation's fight for justice.

This week, I¬†joined my colleagues in co-sponsoring H.R. 14, the John R. Lewis Voting Rights Advancement Act. This critical legislation seeks to restore and enhance the protections originally established by the Voting Rights Act of 1965, tackling modern-day voter suppression and ensuring that every citizen, irrespective of race or background, can exercise their right to vote freely and fairly.

John Lewis embodied the belief that true strength arises from humility, gentleness, patience, and love. It is imperative that we honor his legacy by passing this vital legislation with bipartisan support, allowing us to uphold and advance his unwavering commitment to justice and equality for all.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First¬†

Stephen Hoggard is a Wayne County resident who served our country on active duty in the U.S. Air Force for 20 years. 

Stephen is a dedicated and passionate Veterans Service Officer (VSO) at the North Carolina State Veterans Home in Kinston. In this critical role, he assists veterans with understanding their benefits and filing claims to ensure they receive the support they deserve. As the primary VSO at the state home, he manages all claims and oversees admitting veterans into the facility. 

Stephen's dedication also goes beyond his official duties. When veterans pass away without family or friends, he ensures they receive a respectful burial and funeral service. His unwavering commitment makes a meaningful impact on the lives of those who have served our country, and we are grateful.

Name: LaMalfa, Doug
text:
Nobody is excited about passing another Continuing Resolution, I‚Äôm certainly not. But after years of reckless spending and budget games from the Biden administration we‚Äôre staring down yet another government shutdown with no time to get real reforms in place. Shutting down the government helps no one. It disrupts important services, costs taxpayers even more in the long run, and ultimately solves nothing. Passing a CR isn‚Äôt endorsing the status quo, it‚Äôs giving us the time we need to tackle spending better.

Under President Trump‚Äôs direction, efforts are underway to uncover excess spending, but sorting the good from the bad in the federal government takes time. The public gave President Trump and Congress a mandate to rein in government spending, and passing the CR is our best shot at going after true waste, cutting taxes, and putting America back on a responsible path. We are working to cut taxes, reduce the size and scope of government in our lives, enforce our borders, end ridiculous government waste, and stop all benefits for those in our country illegally, while protecting Social Security, Medicare, and Medicaid.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
Congress has to pass this bill to strengthen the Voting Rights Act of 1965. 

It‚Äôll create a modern-day framework for ending voter suppression and identify states with a history of voter discrimination.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
60 years later, the work isn‚Äôt done.

John Lewis' march across the bridge left us a legacy that includes the John Lewis Voting Rights Advancement Act.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
The marches played a major role in passing the Voting Rights Act of 1965, which eliminated racial discrimination in voting.

It banned literacy tests and other unfair practices, symbolizing a major legislative victory for Black Americans.

Today, I hosted a roundtable discussion in Hazard with the @NashvilleCorps, @HuntingtonCorps & the Louisville Corps for our local elected leaders who serve Eastern Kentucky counties that have been impacted by recent flooding. We reviewed successful Army Corps projects that have helped save communities along the Cumberland River from catastrophic flooding, and the work that is still needed on the Cumberland, and additional flood control projects that are necessary on the Kentucky River and the Big Sandy River. 

On-going projects include a Kentucky River Flood Control Study and flood prevention in Beattyville, Coal Run and Paintsville, among others.

Name: Morrison, Kelly
text:
Today marks 60 years since Bloody Sunday ‚Äì when hundreds of peaceful demonstrators marching in support of equal voting rights were brutally attacked by state troopers. This was a pivotal moment in our nation's civil rights movement, and led to the passage of the landmark Voting Rights Act of 1965.

I'm in Alabama with my colleagues this weekend to honor the bravery and sacrifice of those Americans who put their lives on the line and fought to better fulfill the promise of America.

And we're turning our remembrance into action: this week, every single Democrat in the House joined together to introduce the John R. Lewis Voting Rights Advancement Act to restore and modernize the protections of the 1965 Voting Rights Act, address modern-day voter suppression, and ensure every American has equal access to the ballot box.

Today I met with the incredible residents of the Upper Makefield Task Force to further collaborate on our collective efforts. Months have passed since the Sunoco Pipeline leak sent jet fuel and other hazardous compounds into our community‚Äôs wells, and still, the uncertainty remains. That is unacceptable.

And that is why, immediately following today‚Äôs meeting, I repeated my call on Pipeline and Hazardous Materials Safety Administration (PHMSA) Acting Administrator Ben Kochman to shut down this pipeline.  Until we have indisputable proof that this pipeline poses no further risk, it must remain offline. Anything less is reckless and irresponsible.

From the very start, I have fought for full transparency, real accountability, and a response that meets the gravity of this crisis‚Äînot just from Energy Transfer, but from every government agency, at all levels of government, who have any piece of oversight jurisdiction in this matter. Thus far, the answers we have received are insufficient‚Äîour community deserves more than reassurances.

This is our home, and I will not stop fighting until every well is restored, and every family has been made completely whole, in every way, shape and form.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
On #InternationalWomensDay, we celebrate the trailblazers, pioneers, and everyday heroes who have shaped our nation. But honoring women‚Äôs history means more than just recognizing their contributions‚Äîit means ensuring their stories are told, celebrated, and preserved for generations to come.
 
That‚Äôs why I‚Äôm leading the bipartisan charge to secure a permanent home for the Smithsonian American Women‚Äôs History Museum on the National Mall‚Äîwhere the defining stories of our nation are told. In 2020, I successfully fought to establish the museum, but a museum without a home cannot fulfill its mission.
 
America‚Äôs story is incomplete without the women who built it. Their courage, resilience, and leadership deserve a place at the heart of our capital, alongside the monuments that define our history.
 
This bill is about more than just a building‚Äîit‚Äôs about ensuring that every visitor and student who walks the National Mall is immersed in the rich tapestry of our nation‚Äôs history, and that every young girl sees herself reflected in its story, knowing that her potential is boundless.
 
Women‚Äôs history is American history, and it‚Äôs time we honor it as such. Let‚Äôs make history‚Äîby ensuring it‚Äôs preserved where it belongs.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
An incredible morning at the annual Dias Fellowship Leadership Conference! It was an honor to engage with such a talented group of emerging leaders‚Äîdriven, thoughtful, and committed to making a real impact. The Dias Fellowship, thanks to the visionary leadership of Anne Dias and Ken Griffin, provides an opportunity for fellows to study at both the Harvard Business and Kennedy Schools, fostering bold ideas, global perspectives, and the spirit of public service.
 
A special thank you to Kieron Stopforth‚Äîa Dias Scholar alum and leader in the sustainable energy industry‚Äîand all the fellows for such an insightful discussion on leadership, collaboration, and the responsibility of driving meaningful change.
 
Our conversation reinforced a fundamental truth: Strong leaders don‚Äôt stand alone‚Äîthey bring people together. They listen first, seek solutions outside of echo chambers, and understand that compromise is not a concession but the foundation of lasting change.
 
Thank you again to Anne and the entire Dias community for the opportunity to be part of this important conversation!

Name: Cornyn, John
text: On this day in 1936, a fifty-eight-mile power line near Bartlett, Texas, was energized, according to some sources the first in the nation under the Rural Electrification Administration. @TxStHistAssoc

Name: Cornyn, John
text: The REA had an incalculable impact on life in rural Texas, especially in the Panhandle, which had become something of a proving ground for New Deal programs thanks to the influence of Marvin Jones, chairman of the House Agricultural Committee.

Name: Cornyn, John
text: When President Franklin D. Roosevelt began the REA in May 1935, only about 2 percent of the farms in Texas (and only about 10 percent nationally) had electricity.

Name: Cornyn, John
text: The REA first brought electric power to the rural Panhandle in Deaf Smith County in 1937. By 1965, instead of only 2 percent of Texas farms with electricity, there were only 2 percent without electricity.

Name: Waltz, Michael
text:
National Security Advisor Mike Waltz spoke¬†on Sunday morning¬†with Iraqi Prime Minister Mohammed Shiaa¬†al-Sudani. ¬†The National Security Advisor wished Prime Minister Al-Sudani a Ramadan Kareem, and expressed his concerns regarding the recent flooding in Baghdad.

Mr. Waltz emphasized the importance of moving towards a win-win relationship based on mutual security interests and enhanced trade. ¬†Mr. Waltz noted that the decision to not renew the waiver of sanctions on Iranian electricity exports was consistent with President Trump‚Äôs ‚Äúmaximum pressure‚Äù strategy on Iran, and that pressure on Iran would increase if Iran continued to develop a nuclear weapons capability and support terrorism across the region, including in Iraq. ¬†

Mr. Waltz welcomed the Iraqi Prime Minister‚Äôs efforts to achieve energy independence for Iraq, and encouraged the Iraqi government to welcome more western and U.S. energy companies into Iraq‚Äôs oil and gas sectors. ¬†The National Security Advisor urged the Iraqi government to work with the Kurdistan Regional Government to address remaining contract disputes and pay arrears owed to U.S. energy companies, and also requested that the Iraqi government¬†retain¬†an investment coordinator to work with U.S. companies seeking to¬†invest and¬†operate in Iraq. ¬†

The National Security Advisor thanked the Prime Minister for his commitment to the bilateral U.S-Iraqi relationship, and emphasized the Trump administration‚Äôs commitment to deepening energy and economic ties between the two countries to benefit both the American and Iraqi peoples.

Name: Kelly, Mark
text: Just left Ukraine. What I saw proved to me we can‚Äôt give up on the Ukrainian people. Everyone wants this war to end, but any agreement has to protect Ukraine‚Äôs security and can‚Äôt be a giveaway to Putin. Let me tell you about my trip and why it‚Äôs important we stand with Ukraine.üßµ https://t.co/6kOw1tTgS6

Name: Kelly, Mark
text: Hospitals should never be targets in war, but Putin is a war criminal who targets hospitals routinely. I visited one in Kyiv. Injured soldiers told me how they want to get back to the fight. Nurses there shared their stories of the invasion with me through tears. Stories of violence that women and children of Ukraine suffered during the invasion. These nurses told me how they witnessed Russian soldiers raping children in front of their parents and then murdering these children in front of their parents. Horrendous war crimes which can never be forgiven. Donald Trump says he trusts Putin and is trying to make him look like a friend and a good guy. I look forward to seeing Putin rot in prison.

Name: Kelly, Mark
text: This war started with what Putin thought would be a three-day operation to take Kyiv and control of all of Ukraine. Now three years later, that hasn't happened. American and allied support has been a big reason why, but I saw how cutting it off now risks everything so many Ukrainians have laid down their lives for. And while our support hasn‚Äôt been free, we haven‚Äôt sent even half of what President Trump says.

Name: Kelly, Mark
text: The pause of military aid has only made it harder for Ukraine in their fight against Russia. They are running low on certain weapons which have made it most of the way to Ukraine. Stopping the transfer of these weapons only helps the Russians. The Russians will become more confident and try to drive a harder bargain in ceasefire talks. This isn‚Äôt rocket science. We should be negotiating from a position of strength.

Name: Kelly, Mark
text: Ukraine did not start this war, and they did not ask for the constant missile and drone attacks that have terrorized the population. Government officials who can‚Äôt acknowledge factual information should reevaluate their career choices.

Name: Kelly, Mark
text: Donald Trump is trying to weaken Ukraine‚Äôs hand and we are owed an explanation. If Putin gains ground he won‚Äôt agree to a ceasefire and will eventually threaten a NATO ally and this puts American troops and the American people at risk.

Name: Kelly, Mark
text: I met with Ukrainian pilots, one who I had met in Arizona when he was learning to fly the F-16. They are flying challenging combat missions against the Russians who are protected by a considerable electronic warfare and surface to air missile system defense. They‚Äôve learned a lot and they are getting better and having more success. When Trump cut off these pilots from US intelligence that they need to plan their missions, he blinded them to the threat and put them and their aircraft at risk. But worse than that, it helps the Russians advance further into Ukrainian territory and murder more Ukrainians. President Trump says the Russians are ‚Äúhitting them hard‚Äù in a tone of voice that implies approval. It is sickening to see from an American President. ‚ÄúHitting them hard‚Äù means more dead Ukrainian kids.

Name: Kelly, Mark
text: I saw the innovation and fighting spirit of the Ukrainians up close. It was embodied in their military members, everyday people and by these students who are aviation engineers using their spare time to help Ukrainians innovate in their military. They now have a defense industrial base that we should envy and that we can learn from. They have an innovation cycle measured in days while ours is years. We should be learning from it, not slowing it down.

Name: Kelly, Mark
text: Lastly I visited the Wall of Remembrance to pay tribute to Ukraine‚Äôs dead soldiers. I‚Äôm bringing back what I saw and learned from Ukrainian leaders, servicemembers and the Ukrainian people to show the direct impact our support is having on the ground. The safety and security of Ukraine is tied to the safety and security of the United States. Let me explain why.

Name: Kelly, Mark
text: The world will become a very cold and lonely place if we continue this ridiculous ‚Äúscrew you, go it alone‚Äù foreign policy. It‚Äôs dumb and it won‚Äôt age well and puts you and your kids and your grandkids at risk. America is the strongest, richest country in the world. We didn‚Äôt get there by being bullies like Putin, we got there by leading from the front and bringing our allies. That‚Äôs why I‚Äôll continue to share with everyone who will listen why we must keep supporting Ukraine.

Name: Kelly, Mark
text: Finally, if we stand with Ukraine they will be there for us. This country has a fighting spirit and a depth of experience and kickassness unmatched anywhere in the world today. These are the people you want in your corner. My goal in the Senate is and will continue to be to keep us out of wars. I think that is true for most combat veterans like me. We want to stay out of the fight. But when things go sideways and we find ourselves on the battlefield in a foreign land or God forbid, at home, the first call I‚Äôd want to make is to our Ukrainian friends. I know they would be there for us if we are there for them.

Name: Kelly, Mark
text: If we abandon our ally Ukraine, we will be viewed by other countries including our other allies as untrustworthy and in the future we shouldn‚Äôt expect their help. As significant as that is, what is a bigger deal is the reaction we would see from China. The Chinese watch everything and they want to take Taiwan. If they view our partnerships and our loyalty to our allies as weak they are more likely to try to take Taiwan by force. If that happens, this President or any future President will have to make one of the most consequential decisions in the history of our country. My goal is to avoid that decision. We avoid that by strengthening our alliances, not weakening them.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Kevin and Kristin had a vision. As first-generation farmers, they established Like a Mustard Seed Farm in Perkasie, creating a space that is more than just a farm‚Äîit serves as a place for learning, nourishment, and community. However, when local zoning and sanitation issues threatened to halt their operations, they sought our help, and we got to work.

Together, we navigated through the challenges and red tape, coordinating with county officials and the Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Protection (DEP) to find a solution that allowed their farm to continue welcoming our families, educating our young minds, and strengthening our local food system.

Their farm stands as a testament to the idea that even the smallest seed‚Äîof faith, effort, and community‚Äîcan grow into something significant. We share this belief; when obstacles arise in our community, we are committed to removing them.

Thank you, Kevin and Kristin, for your remarkable contributions to our community‚Äîhere‚Äôs to a great season ahead and continued success!

Thousands of Afghans sacrificed a great deal to support our service members during the NATO mission in Afghanistan. Yet, since taking office President Trump‚Äôs executive orders have stranded tens of thousands of these allies under Taliban oppression. Name: Whitesides, George
text:
Proud to join @AsmPilarSchiavo, Mayor Bill Miranda, and Councilmember Patsy Ayala to represent the #SCV at a stakeholder meeting with local leaders today. We spoke about the importance of addressing the Administration‚Äôs recent federal funding pauses and cuts, and how local organizations are being impacted.

text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 241 BC, The Battle of the Aegates, the final naval clash of the First Punic War between Rome and Carthage, took place.  

In response to Rome blockading its strongholds in Sicily, Carthage sent a fleet to deliver supplies. However, the Roman fleet intercepted and decisively defeated them.

Following the defeat, Carthage sought peace, leading to the Treaty of Lutatius. Carthage surrendered Sicily to Rome and agreed to pay heavy reparations. This victory established Rome as the dominant military power in the western Mediterranean.

Today, we celebrate the incredible life and legacy of Harriet Tubman.

She wasn‚Äôt just a conductor of the Underground Railroad‚Äîshe was a fighter, a healer, a leader, and a woman of deep faith. She risked everything to lead dozens of enslaved people to freedom, without ever getting caught. But did you know she was also a Civil War spy, a nurse, a suffragist, and a mother?

Born Araminta ‚ÄúMinty‚Äù Ross in Maryland, she later took the name Harriet after her mother. When she realized she was about to be sold, she made the impossible choice to leave everything behind‚Äîincluding her husband‚Äîto find freedom. And she didn‚Äôt stop there. Time and time again, she went back to bring others to safety, guided only by her instincts and an unshakable belief that she was doing God‚Äôs work. #HarrietTubmanDay #Courage #Legacy

text: 1.¬†¬†Get rid of dark money in politics.¬†Getting this corrupting toxin out of our elections enjoys powerful public support all across the country; even slightly better in red-leaning districts. Yet most voters don‚Äôt know who opposes and who defends dark money.

text: 2.¬†¬†Spotlight the climate denial machine.¬†The fossil fuel industry runs the biggest and most corrupting political influence and disinformation operation in U.S. history.¬†Calling it out is important truth-telling as the economic dangers of climate change fall upon us.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: 3.¬†¬†Make Polluters Pay.¬†The climate denial machine perpetuates a free-to-pollute business model that violates basic principles of economics, fairness and morality, and puts us in grave danger.¬†Polluters should pay, and people know that.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: 5.¬†¬†De-corrupt the Tax Code.¬†The unfair advantages of the very well-off and the biggest corporations must be corrected, both to lift economic pressure on families and to strengthen our nation‚Äôs finances.¬†Billionaire freeloaders must be brought to heel.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: 6.¬†¬†Reduce Corporate Political Influence.¬†America‚Äôs fifty-year experiment with corporate influence in our democracy, contrary to the plain wisdom of the Founders, has proven to be a dangerous failure.¬†Out they go; back to government by the people.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: 4.¬†¬†Restore the Court.¬†The billionaire-funded scheme to capture the Supreme Court deserves equal attention to the climate denial scheme, and they overlap.¬†The reforms we seek ‚Äî a proper ethics code and term limits ‚Äî are very popular, even across party lines.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: We can achieve a gentle revolution, improving the economic conditions of Americans, restoring their voice as citizens, and rooting out massive present levels of corruption. Then, people will both do better in America and feel better about America.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
This afternoon, I had the honor of joining my friends at the @acog during their 43rd Annual Congressional Leadership Conference. These medical professionals are the backbone of maternal healthcare, and I will always stand with them in the fight to protect the lives of mothers and babies.

The United States has the highest maternal mortality rate among high-income nations. In 2021 alone, 1,205 mothers lost their lives to pregnancy-related causes‚Äîa crisis that demands urgent action.

We know research can uncover the root causes of this crisis and lead to real solutions. That‚Äôs why I‚Äôm fighting to advance maternal health research through the bipartisan NIH IMPROVE Act‚Äîpermanently authorizing funding for IMPROVE and ensuring NIH has the resources needed to continue its vital work.

Our OB-GYNs are on the front lines of this fight every day, providing the care that keeps moms and babies healthy. I will always support them, push for the resources they need, and work to ensure they can continue delivering the highest standard of care.

Our fathers were there then, and we stand with them now, carrying forward the fight for democracy, equality, and the right to vote. The struggle continues, but so does our resolve.

We walk in their footsteps so future generations won‚Äôt have to march for the same rights. Let‚Äôs keep moving forward. #BloodySunday60 #GoodTrouble #Selma

Name: Brownley, Julia
text: I will not support a continuing resolution that undermines the constitutional responsibility entrusted to Congress. Article 1 of the U.S. Constitution grants Congress ‚Äì not the President or unelected officials ‚Äì the power of the purse. That is because our founders understood that only the elected representatives of the American people should pass laws and decide how taxpayer funds should be spent. This power held by Congress remains an essential element of our Constitution, intentionally designed to protect us from authoritarianism. The President does not have the unilateral authority to eliminate federal programs created by Congress, nor can any President transfer such authority to an unelected, unvetted, and unaccountable billionaire. Yet, this resolution weakens Congress' power of the purse, yielding greater control over how taxpayer dollars are spent to the President and his billionaire allies.

Name: Perez, Marie Gluesenkamp
text:
Today, I voted against a flawed Continuing Resolution, because we should work on a bipartisan basis to pass a bill that works for communities like mine.

My highest priority in Congress is to defend the interests of #WA03 ‚Äì and the path of chaos and uncertainty today‚Äôs partisan CR presents is at best counterproductive and at worst empowers the most partisan members of Congress to have the most say in how our public dollars are spent.

This CR fails to fund much-needed community-led investments across SW WA to support public safety, veterans, students, farmers, and utility infrastructure.

It lowers funding levels for the U.S. Geological Survey and NOAA, as our communities face concerns about seismic monitoring in the region and layoffs of employees that provide vital weather data for maritime safety.

It would also cut U.S. Army Corps of Engineers construction funding by 44% ‚Äì which could impact efforts to keep goods moving safely on our waterways and manage flood risk ‚Äì while halting new projects.

This legislation cuts nearly $800M from VA facility construction, doesn't protect funding levels for veterans homelessness, mental health, and addiction programs, and provides no advance appropriations for the Toxic Exposures Fund to avoid lapses in support for heroes suffering from service-connected illnesses.

It also decreases funding for state, private, and Tribal forestry programs that support forest management and prevent wildfire, small business development projects, clean drinking water grants, state and local law enforcement programs, and the Community Connect Program, which has supported rural broadband expansion in Lewis County.

A $20.2 billion cut to IRS operations and tax enforcement would also make it more difficult to investigate complex forms of tax evasion by the wealthiest Americans ‚Äì which delivers a significant return on investment.

The DoD has also never operated for an entire fiscal year under a CR, which raises concerns about impacts on our military readiness.

Congress too frequently relies on stopgap measures, rather than completing full-year bipartisan funding solutions. As a member of the House Appropriations Committee, I know how important it is to protect Congress‚Äôs power of the purse ‚Äì and provide guidance to agencies on how to effectively spend taxpayer dollars.

Congress needs to do the hard work of passing regular appropriations bills, rather than ceding our Constitutional obligations by relying on a hastily constructed CR.

I came to Congress to vote on the merits of bills. As an independent voice for SW WA, I‚Äôll continue to put hardworking families first out of fierce loyalty to our communities.

Folks across #WA03 want responsible governance ‚Äì and I look forward to finding bipartisan opportunities to address our most urgent priorities.

I urge all of my colleagues on both sides to get back to the table and negotiate a responsible, bipartisan fiscal package that meets the needs of communities like ours.

Name: Roy, Chip
text:
üö® REP. ROY STATEMENT ON HOUSE PASSAGE OF CONTINUING RESOLUTION üö®

"Today, I voted to effectively freeze spending levels for six more months and to give runway for the Trump Administration to continue its efforts to root out wasteful spending. House Republicans and President Trump are moving quickly to clean up the mess left by Chuck Schumer and Joe Biden, who refused to pass a budget or any appropriations bills ‚Äì despite the House GOP passing five off the floor, and all 12 out of committee.

Notably, this ‚Äúcontinuing resolution‚Äù excludes earmarks, modestly reduces year-over-year spending, and most importantly, prevents Democrats from purposefully shutting down DOGE, President Trump, and Russ Vought from uncovering the billions in waste, fraud, and abuse that has been going on for decades.  The American people are now seeing that this whole town ‚Äì THE SWAMP ‚Äì has been wasting their money on absurd expenditures.

But this is just one more step, of many, in the spending fight.  

Now, our focus must be on supporting the President‚Äôs efforts to impound and rescind unnecessary spending, passing appropriations bills for FY26 at a low topline including many of the DOGE-identified cuts, and then finalizing a conservative reconciliation package. We must cut the massive inflation tax resulting from rampant spending by working to deliver on spending reductions ABOVE the $2 trillion FLOOR the House passed in our budget along with making tax cuts permanent.

It‚Äôs now or never."

Name: Estes, Ron
text: Today, the National Transportation Safety Board released its preliminary report on the collision between American Eagle Flight 5342 and Black Hawk PAT 25. Our state and nation continue mourning the 67 lives lost in the tragedy of the Jan. 29 collision over the Potomac River. The NTSB's preliminary report contains many of the critical facts that have been reported throughout the past month, including details into what happened in both cockpits on that tragic night, as well as two urgent safety recommendations to prevent a future incident at Reagan National Airport. I fully support the NTSB, FAA, Army, and all other involved agencies and parties as they work to investigate the collision, especially the Department of Transportation's support and implementation of safety recommendations and improvements. While nothing can ever replace the lives lost on Flight 5342 and PAT 25, my prayer is that these insights, recommendations and changes help bring healing and closure to the families of those grieving.
